<edge source="concept.article_of_faith" target="concept.faith" id="edge.concept.article_of_faith.part_of.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.article_of_faith.part_of.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.article_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d8">Article of Faith</data>
  <data key="d9">doctrine</data>
  <data key="d10">part_of</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.concept-article-of-faith-part-of-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">iv) that an article is composed of words each pronounced singly and separately, thus: "Your passion, your voice, your look, have struck terror into your foes." Hence matters of Christian faith are said to contain distinct articles, in so far as they are divided into parts, and fit together</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.charity" target="concept.friendship_with_god" id="edge.concept.charity.defined_as.concept.friendship_with_god">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.charity.defined_as.concept.friendship_with_god</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d8">Charity</data>
  <data key="d9">virtue</data>
  <data key="d10">defined_as</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.friendship_with_god</data>
  <data key="d12">Friendship with God</data>
  <data key="d13">doctrine</data>
  <data key="d14">doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.concept-charity-defined-as-concept-friendship-with-god-st-ii-ii-q023-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Accordingly, since there is a communication between man and God , inasmuch as He communicates His happiness to us, some kind of friendship must needs be based on this same communication, of which it is written ( 1 Corinthians 1:9 ): " God is faithful: by Whom you are called unto the fellowship of His Son." The love which is based on this communication, is charity : wherefore it is evident that charity is the friendship of man for God .</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.charity" target="concept.virtue" id="edge.concept.charity.species_of.concept.virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.charity.species_of.concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d8">Charity</data>
  <data key="d9">virtue</data>
  <data key="d10">species_of</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Virtue</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.concept-charity-species-of-concept-virtue-st-ii-ii-q023-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Wherefore, it follows that charity is a virtue , for, since charity attains God , it unites us to God , as evidenced by the authority of Augustine quoted above.</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.eternal_life" target="concept.grace" id="edge.concept.eternal_life.requires.concept.grace">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.eternal_life.requires.concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.eternal_life</data>
  <data key="d8">Eternal Life</data>
  <data key="d9">end</data>
