</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001.a004" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a004.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a004.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 a.4 — Can the object of faith be anything seen?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q001-a004-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Faith implies assent of the intellect to that which is believed</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001.a004" target="concept.object_of_faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a004.treated_in.concept.object_of_faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a004.treated_in.concept.object_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 a.4 — Can the object of faith be anything seen?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.object_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Object of Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">doctrine</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q001-a004-treated-in-concept-object-of-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Faith implies assent of the intellect to that which is believed . Now the intellect assents to a thing in two ways. First, through being moved to assent by its very object, which is known either by itself (as in the case of first principles, which are held by</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001.a005" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a005.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a005.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 a.5 — Can it be anything known?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q001-a005-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">On like manner it may happen that what is an object of vision or scientific knowledge for one man , even in the state of a wayfarer, is, for another man , an object of faith , because he does not know it by demonstration</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001.a005" target="concept.object_of_faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a005.treated_in.concept.object_of_faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a005.treated_in.concept.object_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 a.5 — Can it be anything known?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.object_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Object of Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">doctrine</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q001-a005-treated-in-concept-object-of-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">On like manner it may happen that what is an object of vision or scientific knowledge for one man , even in the state of a wayfarer, is, for another man , an object of faith , because he does not know it by demonstration</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001.a006" target="concept.article_of_faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a006.treated_in.concept.article_of_faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a006.treated_in.concept.article_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 a.6 — Should the things to be believed be divided into a certain number of articles?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.article_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Article of Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">doctrine</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q001-a006-treated-in-concept-article-of-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">the word "article" is apparently derived from the Greek; for the Greek arthron [Cf. William of Auxerre , Summa Aurea] which the Latin renders "articulus," signifies a fitting together of distinct parts: wherefore the small parts of the body which fit together</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001.a006" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a006.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a006.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 a.6 — Should the things to be believed be divided into a certain number of articles?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q001-a006-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">iv) that an article is composed of words each pronounced singly and separately, thus: "Your passion, your voice, your look, have struck terror into your foes." Hence matters of Christian faith are said to contain distinct articles, in so far as they are divided into parts, and fit together</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001.a007" target="concept.article_of_faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a007.treated_in.concept.article_of_faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a007.treated_in.concept.article_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 a.7 — These articles: are they of faith for all times?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.article_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Article of Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">doctrine</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q001-a007-treated-in-concept-article-of-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">The articles of faith stand in the same relation to the doctrine of faith , as self-evident principles to a teaching based on natural reason</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001.a007" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a007.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a007.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 a.7 — These articles: are they of faith for all times?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q001-a007-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">The articles of faith stand in the same relation to the doctrine of faith , as self-evident principles to a teaching based on natural reason</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001.a008" target="concept.article_of_faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a008.treated_in.concept.article_of_faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a008.treated_in.concept.article_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 a.8 — The number of articles</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.article_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Article of Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">doctrine</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q001-a008-treated-in-concept-article-of-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above (Articles 4 and 6 ), to faith those things in themselves belong, the sight of which we shall enjoy in eternal life , and by which we are brought to eternal life . Now two things are proposed to us to be seen in eternal life : viz. the secret of</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001.a008" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a008.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a008.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 a.8 — The number of articles</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q001-a008-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above (Articles 4 and 6 ), to faith those things in themselves belong, the sight of which we shall enjoy in eternal life , and by which we are brought to eternal life</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001.a009" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a009.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a009.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001.a009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 a.9 — The manner of embodying the articles in a symbol</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q001-a009-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a009-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Hence the need for the truth of faith to be collected together, so that it might the more easily be proposed to all, lest anyone might stray from the truth through ignorance of the faith</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001.a009" target="concept.symbol_of_faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a009.treated_in.concept.symbol_of_faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a009.treated_in.concept.symbol_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001.a009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 a.9 — The manner of embodying the articles in a symbol</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.symbol_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Symbol of Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">doctrine</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q001-a009-treated-in-concept-symbol-of-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a009-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">It is from its being a collection of maxims of faith that the symbol [The Greek symballein ] takes its name.</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001.a010" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a010.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a010.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001.a010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 a.10 — Who has the right to propose a symbol of faith?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q001-a010-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a010-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Consequently to publish a new edition of the symbol belongs to that authority which is empowered to decide matters of faith finally, so that they may be held by all with unshaken faith</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q001.a010" target="concept.symbol_of_faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a010.treated_in.concept.symbol_of_faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q001.a010.treated_in.concept.symbol_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q001.a010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.1 a.10 — Who has the right to propose a symbol of faith?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.symbol_of_faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Symbol of Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">doctrine</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q001-a010-treated-in-concept-symbol-of-faith-st-ii-ii-q001-a010-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q001.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above (Objection 1), a new edition of the symbol becomes necessary in order to set aside the errors that may arise</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a001" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a001.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a001.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.1 — Is charity friendship?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a001-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Accordingly, since there is a communication between man and God , inasmuch as He communicates His happiness to us, some kind of friendship must needs be based on this same communication, of which it is written ( 1 Corinthians 1:9 ): " God is faithful: by Whom you are called unto the fellowship of His Son." The love which is based on this communication, is charity : wherefore it is evident that charity is the friendship of man for God .</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a001" target="concept.friendship_with_god" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a001.treated_in.concept.friendship_with_god">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a001.treated_in.concept.friendship_with_god</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.1 — Is charity friendship?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.friendship_with_god</data>
  <data key="d12">Friendship with God</data>
  <data key="d13">doctrine</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a001-treated-in-concept-friendship-with-god-st-ii-ii-q023-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Accordingly, since there is a communication between man and God , inasmuch as He communicates His happiness to us, some kind of friendship must needs be based on this same communication, of which it is written ( 1 Corinthians 1:9 ): " God is faithful: by Whom you are called unto the fellowship of His Son." The love which is based on this communication, is charity : wherefore it is evident that charity is the friendship of man for God .</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a002" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a002.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a002.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.2 — Is it something created in the soul?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a002-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">The Master looks thoroughly into this question in 17 of the First Book, and concludes that charity is not something created in the soul , but is the Holy Ghost Himself dwelling in the mind</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a003" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a003.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a003.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.3 — Is it a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a003-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Wherefore, it follows that charity is a virtue , for, since charity attains God , it unites us to God , as evidenced by the authority of Augustine quoted above.</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a003" target="concept.virtue" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a003.treated_in.concept.virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a003.treated_in.concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.3 — Is it a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Virtue</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a003-treated-in-concept-virtue-st-ii-ii-q023-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Wherefore human virtue which is the principle of all man's good acts consists in following the rule of human acts , which is twofold, as stated above ( II-II:17:1 ), viz</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a004" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a004.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a004.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.4 — Is it a special virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a004-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">But the Divine good , inasmuch as it is the object of happiness , has a special aspect of good , wherefore the love of charity , which is the love of that good , is a special kind of love</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a005" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a005.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a005.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.5 — Is it one virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a005-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Charity , as stated above ( Article 1 ) is a kind of friendship of man for God</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a006" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a006.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a006.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.6 — Is it the greatest of the virtues?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a006-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">But faith and hope attain God indeed in so far as we derive from Him the knowledge of truth or the acquisition of good , whereas charity attains God Himself that it may rest in Him, but not that something may accrue to us from Him</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a007" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a007.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a007.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.7 — Is any true virtue possible without it?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a007-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">The ultimate and principal good of man is the enjoyment of God , according to Psalm 72:28 : "It is good for me to adhere to God ," and to this good man is ordered by charity</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a008" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a008.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a008.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.8 — Is it the form of the virtues?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a008-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now it is evident, in accordance with what has been said ( Article 7 ), that it is charity which directs the acts of all other virtues to the last end, and which, consequently, also gives the form to all other acts of virtue : and it is precisely in this sense that charity is called the form of the virtues , for these are called virtues in relation to "informed" acts.</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a008" target="concept.form_of_virtues" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a008.treated_in.concept.form_of_virtues">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a008.treated_in.concept.form_of_virtues</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.8 — Is it the form of the virtues?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.form_of_virtues</data>
  <data key="d12">Form of the Virtues</data>
  <data key="d13">doctrine</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a008-treated-in-concept-form-of-virtues-st-ii-ii-q023-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now it is evident, in accordance with what has been said ( Article 7 ), that it is charity which directs the acts of all other virtues to the last end, and which, consequently, also gives the form to all other acts of virtue : and it is precisely in this sense that charity is called the form of the virtues , for these are called virtues in relation to "informed" acts.</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a008" target="concept.virtue" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a008.treated_in.concept.virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a008.treated_in.concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.8 — Is it the form of the virtues?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Virtue</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a008-treated-in-concept-virtue-st-ii-ii-q023-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q023.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now it is evident, in accordance with what has been said ( Article 7 ), that it is charity which directs the acts of all other virtues to the last end, and which, consequently, also gives the form to all other acts of virtue : and it is precisely in this sense that charity is called the form of the virtues , for these are called virtues in relation to "informed" acts.</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a001" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a001.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a001.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.1 — Is prudence in the will or in the reason?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a001-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Wherefore it is manifest that prudence belongs directly to the cognitive, and not to the sensitive faculty, because by the latter we know nothing but what is within reach and offers itself to the senses: while to obtain knowledge of the future from knowledge of the present or past, which pertains to prudence , belongs properly to the reason, because this is done by a process of comparison</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a001" target="concept.reason" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a001.treated_in.concept.reason">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a001.treated_in.concept.reason</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.1 — Is prudence in the will or in the reason?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.reason</data>
  <data key="d12">Reason</data>
  <data key="d13">faculty</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a001-treated-in-concept-reason-st-ii-ii-q047-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Wherefore it is manifest that prudence belongs directly to the cognitive, and not to the sensitive faculty, because by the latter we know nothing but what is within reach and offers itself to the senses: while to obtain knowledge of the future from knowledge of the present or past, which pertains to prudence , belongs properly to the reason, because this is done by a process of comparison</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a002" target="concept.practical_reason" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a002.treated_in.concept.practical_reason">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a002.treated_in.concept.practical_reason</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.2 — If in the reason, is it only in the practical, or also in the speculative reason?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.practical_reason</data>
  <data key="d12">Practical Reason</data>
  <data key="d13">faculty</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a002-treated-in-concept-practical-reason-st-ii-ii-q047-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">vi, 5) "a prudent man is one who is capable of taking good counsel." Now counsel is about things that we have to do in relation to some end: and the reason that deals with things to be done for an end is the practical reason</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a002" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a002.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a002.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.2 — If in the reason, is it only in the practical, or also in the speculative reason?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a002-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Hence it is evident that prudence resides only in the practical reason.</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a003" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a003.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a003.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.3 — Does it take cognizance of singulars?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a003-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1, Reply to Objection 3 ), to prudence belongs not only the consideration of the reason, but also the application to action, which is the end of the practical reason</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a004" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a004.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a004.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.4 — Is it virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a004-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now it belongs to prudence , as stated above ( Article 1, Reply to Objection 3</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a004" target="concept.virtue" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a004.treated_in.concept.virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a004.treated_in.concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.4 — Is it virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Virtue</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a004-treated-in-concept-virtue-st-ii-ii-q047-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">I-II:56:1 ) when we were treating of virtues in general, " virtue is that which makes its possessor good , and his work good likewise." Now good may be understood in a twofold sense: first, materially, for the thing that is good , secondly, formally, under the aspect of good</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a005" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a005.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a005.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.5 — Is it a special virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a005-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Accordingly we must say that since prudence is in the reason, as stated above ( Article 2 ), it is differentiated from the other intellectual virtues by a material difference of objects</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a005" target="concept.virtue" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a005.treated_in.concept.virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a005.treated_in.concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.5 — Is it a special virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Virtue</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a005-treated-in-concept-virtue-st-ii-ii-q047-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">I-II:54:2 ), any habit that has a corresponding special object, distinct from other objects, must needs be a special habit , and if it be a good habit , it must be a special virtue</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a006" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a006.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a006.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.6 — Does it appoint the end to the moral virtues?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a006-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">About these is prudence , which applies universal principles to the particular conclusions of practical matters</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a007" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a007.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a007.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.7 — Does it fix the mean in the moral virtues?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a007-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">But it belongs to the ruling of prudence to decide in what manner and by what means man shall obtain the mean of reason in his deeds</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a008" target="concept.command" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a008.treated_in.concept.command">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a008.treated_in.concept.command</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.8 — Is its proper act command?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.command</data>
  <data key="d12">Command</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a008-treated-in-concept-command-st-ii-ii-q047-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">But the practical reason, which is directed to action, goes further, and its third act is "to command," which act consists in applying to action the things counselled and judged</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a008" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a008.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a008.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.8 — Is its proper act command?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a008-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence is "right reason applied to action," as stated above ( Article 2 )</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a009" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a009.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a009.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.9 — Does solicitude or watchfulness belong to prudence?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a009-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a009-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now this belongs to prudence , whose chief act is a command about what has been already counselled and judged in matters of action</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a009" target="concept.solicitude" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a009.treated_in.concept.solicitude">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a009.treated_in.concept.solicitude</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.9 — Does solicitude or watchfulness belong to prudence?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.solicitude</data>
  <data key="d12">Solicitude</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a009-treated-in-concept-solicitude-st-ii-ii-q047-a009-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">vi, 9) that "one should be quick in carrying out the counsel taken, but slow in taking counsel." Hence it is that solicitude belongs properly to prudence , and for this reason Augustine says (De Morib</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a010" target="concept.common_good" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a010.treated_in.concept.common_good">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a010.treated_in.concept.common_good</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.10 — Does prudence extend to the governing of many?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.common_good</data>
  <data key="d12">Common Good</data>
  <data key="d13">end</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a010-treated-in-concept-common-good-st-ii-ii-q047-a010-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">vi, 8) some have held that prudence does not extend to the common good , but only to the good of the individual , and this because they thought that man is not bound to seek other than his own good</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a010" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a010.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a010.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.10 — Does prudence extend to the governing of many?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a010-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a010-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">vi, 8) some have held that prudence does not extend to the common good , but only to the good of the individual , and this because they thought that man is not bound to seek other than his own good</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a011" target="concept.common_good" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a011.treated_in.concept.common_good">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a011.treated_in.concept.common_good</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a011</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.11 — Is the prudence which regards private good the same in species as that which regards the common good?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.common_good</data>
  <data key="d12">Common Good</data>
  <data key="d13">end</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a011-treated-in-concept-common-good-st-ii-ii-q047-a011-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a011.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">another, "domestic prudence " which is directed to the common good of the home</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a011" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a011.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a011.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a011</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.11 — Is the prudence which regards private good the same in species as that which regards the common good?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a011-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a011-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a011.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Wherefore there must needs be different species of prudence corresponding to these different ends, so that one is " prudence " simply so called, which is directed to one's own good</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a012" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a012.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a012.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a012</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.12 — Is prudence in subjects, or only in their rulers?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a012-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a012-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a012.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence is in the reason</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a013" target="concept.false_prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a013.treated_in.concept.false_prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a013.treated_in.concept.false_prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a013</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.13 — Is prudence in the wicked?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.false_prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">False Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a013-treated-in-concept-false-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a013-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a013.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">There is a false prudence , which takes its name from its likeness to true prudence</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a013" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a013.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a013.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a013</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.13 — Is prudence in the wicked?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a013-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a013-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a013.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence is threefold</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a013" target="concept.prudence_of_flesh" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a013.treated_in.concept.prudence_of_flesh">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a013.treated_in.concept.prudence_of_flesh</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a013</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.13 — Is prudence in the wicked?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence_of_flesh</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence of the Flesh</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a013-treated-in-concept-prudence-of-flesh-st-ii-ii-q047-a013-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a013.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence is threefold. There is a false prudence , which takes its name from its likeness to true prudence . For since a prudent man is one who disposes well of the things that have to be done for a good end, whoever disposes well of such things as are fitting</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a014" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a014.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a014.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a014</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.14 — Is prudence in all good men?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a014-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a014-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a014.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now whoever has grace has charity , so that he must needs have all the other virtues , and hence, since prudence is a virtue , as shown above ( Article 4 ), he must, of necessity , have prudence also.</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a015" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a015.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a015.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a015</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.15 — Is prudence in us naturally?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a015-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a015-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a015.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As shown above ( Article 3 ), prudence includes knowledge both of universals, and of the singular matters of action to which prudence applies the universal principles</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a016" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a016.treated_in.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q047.a016.treated_in.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q047.a016</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.47 a.16 — Is prudence lost by forgetfulness?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d12">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a016-treated-in-concept-prudence-st-ii-ii-q047-a016-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a016.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">But prudence consists not in knowledge alone, but also in an act of the appetite , because as stated above ( Article 8 ), its principal act is one of command, whereby a man applies the knowledge he has, to the purpose of appetition and operation</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a001" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a001.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a001.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.1 — What is justice?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a001-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">The aforesaid definition of justice is fitting if understood aright</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a002" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a002.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a002.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.2 — Is justice always towards another?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a002-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( II-II:57:1 ) since justice by its name implies equality, it denotes essentially relation to another, for a thing is equal, not to itself, but to another</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a003" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a003.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a003.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.3 — Is it a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a003-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">ii, 6, and this can be applied to justice</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a003" target="concept.virtue" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a003.treated_in.concept.virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a003.treated_in.concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.3 — Is it a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Virtue</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a003-treated-in-concept-virtue-st-ii-ii-q058-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">A human virtue is one "which renders a human act and man himself good " [Ethic</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a004" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a004.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a004.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.4 — Is it in the will as its subject?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a004-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now justice does not aim at directing an act of the cognitive power, for we are not said to be just through knowing something aright</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a004" target="concept.will" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a004.treated_in.concept.will">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a004.treated_in.concept.will</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.4 — Is it in the will as its subject?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.will</data>
  <data key="d12">Will</data>
  <data key="d13">faculty</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a004-treated-in-concept-will-st-ii-ii-q058-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">namely, the will which is in the reason and the sensitive appetite which follows on sensitive apprehension, and is divided into the irascible and the concupiscible , as stated in I:81:2</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a005" target="concept.general_justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a005.treated_in.concept.general_justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a005.treated_in.concept.general_justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.5 — Is it a general virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.general_justice</data>
  <data key="d12">General Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a005-treated-in-concept-general-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">It is in this sense that justice is called a general virtue</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a005" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a005.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a005.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.5 — Is it a general virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a005-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Justice, as stated above ( Article 2 ) directs man in his relations with other men</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a006" target="concept.general_justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a006.treated_in.concept.general_justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a006.treated_in.concept.general_justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.6 — As a general virtue, is it essentially the same as every virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.general_justice</data>
  <data key="d12">General Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a006-treated-in-concept-general-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now it is in the latter sense that, according to what has been said ( Article 5 ), legal justice is said to be a general virtue , in as much, to wit, as it directs the acts of the other virtues to its own end, and this is to move all the other virtues by its command</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a006" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a006.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a006.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.6 — As a general virtue, is it essentially the same as every virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a006-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now it is in the latter sense that, according to what has been said ( Article 5 ), legal justice is said to be a general virtue , in as much, to wit, as it directs the acts of the other virtues to its own end, and this is to move all the other virtues by its command</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a007" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a007.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a007.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.7 — Is there a particular justice?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a007-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 6 ), legal justice is not essentially the same as every virtue , and besides legal justice which directs man immediately to the common good , there is a need for other virtues to direct him immediately in matters relating to particular goods: and these virtues may be relative to himself or to another individual person</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a007" target="concept.particular_justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a007.treated_in.concept.particular_justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a007.treated_in.concept.particular_justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.7 — Is there a particular justice?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.particular_justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Particular Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a007-treated-in-concept-particular-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Accordingly, just as in addition to legal justice there is a need for particular virtues to direct man in relation to himself, such as temperance and fortitude , so too besides legal justice there is need for particular justice to direct man in his relations to other individuals .</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a008" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a008.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a008.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.8 — Does particular justice have a matter of its own?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a008-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Consequently, since justice is directed to others, it is not about the entire matter of moral virtue , but only about external actions and things, under a certain special aspect of the object, in so far as one man is related to another through them.</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a009" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a009.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a009.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.9 — Is it about passions, or about operations only?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a009-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a009-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">First from the subject of justice , i.e</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a010" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a010.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a010.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.10 — Is the mean of justice the real mean?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a010-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a010-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">On the other hand, the matter of justice is external operation, in so far as an operation or the thing used in that operation is duly proportionate to another person , wherefore the mean of justice consists in a certain proportion of equality between the external thing and the external person</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a011" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a011.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a011.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a011</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.11 — Is the act of justice to render to everyone his own?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a011-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a011-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a011.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above (Articles 8 and 10 ), the matter of justice is an external operation in so far as either it or the thing we use by it is made proportionate to some other person to whom we are related by justice</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a011" target="concept.rendering_due" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a011.treated_in.concept.rendering_due">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a011.treated_in.concept.rendering_due</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a011</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.11 — Is the act of justice to render to everyone his own?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.rendering_due</data>
  <data key="d12">Rendering Due</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a011-treated-in-concept-rendering-due-st-ii-ii-q058-a011-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a011.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Therefore the proper act of justice is nothing else than to render to each one his own.</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a012" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a012.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a012.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a012</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.12 — Is justice the chief of the moral virtues?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a012-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a012-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q058.a012.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">If we speak of legal justice , it is evident that it stands foremost among all the moral virtues , for as much as the common good transcends the individual good of one person</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q171.a001" target="concept.knowledge" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a001.treated_in.concept.knowledge">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a001.treated_in.concept.knowledge</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q171.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.171 a.1 — Does prophecy pertain to knowledge?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.knowledge</data>
  <data key="d12">Knowledge</data>
  <data key="d13">doctrine</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q171-a001-treated-in-concept-knowledge-st-ii-ii-q171-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q171.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Prophecy first and chiefly consists in knowledge , because, to wit, prophets know things that are far [procul] removed from man's knowledge</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q171.a001" target="concept.prophecy" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a001.treated_in.concept.prophecy">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a001.treated_in.concept.prophecy</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q171.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.171 a.1 — Does prophecy pertain to knowledge?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prophecy</data>
  <data key="d12">Prophecy</data>
  <data key="d13">charism</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q171-a001-treated-in-concept-prophecy-st-ii-ii-q171-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q171.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Prophecy first and chiefly consists in knowledge , because, to wit, prophets know things that are far [procul] removed from man's knowledge</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q171.a002" target="concept.prophecy" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a002.treated_in.concept.prophecy">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a002.treated_in.concept.prophecy</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q171.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.171 a.2 — Is it a habit?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prophecy</data>
  <data key="d12">Prophecy</data>
  <data key="d13">charism</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q171-a002-treated-in-concept-prophecy-st-ii-ii-q171-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q171.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Since then prophecy pertains to a knowledge that surpasses natural reason , as stated above ( Article 1 ), it follows that prophecy requires an intellectual light surpassing the light of natural reason</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q171.a003" target="concept.future_contingents" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a003.treated_in.concept.future_contingents">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a003.treated_in.concept.future_contingents</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q171.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.171 a.3 — Is it only about future contingencies?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.future_contingents</data>
  <data key="d12">Future Contingents</data>
  <data key="d13">object</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q171-a003-treated-in-concept-future-contingents-st-ii-ii-q171-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q171.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">such are future contingencies, the truth of which is indeterminate</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q171.a003" target="concept.prophecy" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a003.treated_in.concept.prophecy">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a003.treated_in.concept.prophecy</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q171.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.171 a.3 — Is it only about future contingencies?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prophecy</data>
  <data key="d12">Prophecy</data>
  <data key="d13">charism</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q171-a003-treated-in-concept-prophecy-st-ii-ii-q171-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q171.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Thus by the ministry of spirits a prophetic revelation concerning the perfections of God and the angels was made to Isaiah 6:1 , where it is written, "I saw the Lord sitting upon a throne high and elevated." Moreover his prophecy contains matters referring to natural bodies, according to the words of Isaiah 40:12 , "Who hath measured the waters in the hollow of His hand," etc</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q171.a004" target="concept.prophecy" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a004.treated_in.concept.prophecy">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a004.treated_in.concept.prophecy</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q171.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.171 a.4 — Does a prophet know all possible matters of prophecy?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prophecy</data>
  <data key="d12">Prophecy</data>
  <data key="d13">charism</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q171-a004-treated-in-concept-prophecy-st-ii-ii-q171-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q171.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Wherefore there is no need for their knowing all possible matters of prophecy</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q171.a005" target="concept.prophecy" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a005.treated_in.concept.prophecy">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a005.treated_in.concept.prophecy</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q171.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.171 a.5 — Does a prophet distinguish that which he perceives by the gift of God, from that which he perceives by his own spirit?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prophecy</data>
  <data key="d12">Prophecy</data>
  <data key="d13">charism</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q171-a005-treated-in-concept-prophecy-st-ii-ii-q171-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q171.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">And those things which we know by Divine instinct are not all manifested with prophetic certitude , for this instinct is something imperfect in the genus of prophecy</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q171.a006" target="concept.prophecy" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a006.treated_in.concept.prophecy">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q171.a006.treated_in.concept.prophecy</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q171.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.171 a.6 — Can anything false be the matter of prophecy?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.prophecy</data>
  <data key="d12">Prophecy</data>
  <data key="d13">charism</data>
  <data key="d14">structural</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q171-a006-treated-in-concept-prophecy-st-ii-ii-q171-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q171.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As may be gathered from what has been said ( 1 and 3 and 5 ), prophecy is a kind of knowledge impressed under the form of teaching on the prophet 's intellect , by Divine revelation</data>
  <data key="d19"></data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
</graph></graphml>